T1  - Marginal Effects of Merit Aid for Low-Income Students*
PY  - 2022
Y1  - 2022/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjab050
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 137
IS  - 2
SP  - 1039
EP  - 1090
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Financial aid from the Susan Thompson Buffett Foundation (STBF) provides comprehensive support to a student population similar to that served by a host of state aid programs. In conjunction with STBF, we randomly assigned aid awards to thousands of Nebraska high school graduates from low-income, minority, and first-generation college households. Randomly assigned STBF awards boost bachelor’s (BA) degree completion for students targeting four-year schools by about 8 points. Degree gains are concentrated among four-year college applicants who would otherwise have been unlikely to pursue a four-year program. Degree effects are mediated by award-induced increases in credits earned toward a BA in the first year of college. The extent of initial four-year college engagement explains differences in impact by target campus and across covariate subgroups. The projected lifetime earnings effect of awards exceeds marginal educational spending for all of the subgroups examined in the study. Projected earnings gains exceed funder costs for urban students and for students with relatively weak academic preparation.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjab050
ER  - 



